.Bxe7  Nxe7  19.Ng5  Qg6  20.Qxg6 !   20.Qxh7+  Qxh7  21.Nxh7  Kxh7  22.Rxe7  Bd5  gives Black drawing chances in the double-rook ending.  20...Nxg6  21.Nxf7  Rxf7  22.Rad1 !  Rxd1  23.Rxd1  Bc6  24.Rd6  Be8  25.Rxa6  White had a winning endgame in Gurgenidze - Anikaev, Kislovodsk 1972.   16...g6  17.Qh6  Nd4  18.Ng5  Bxg5  19.Bxg5  Qd6  20.Rad1  ± White has a very dangerous dynamic advantage, due to the pair of bishops and the exposed black king; for example  20...Rae8 ?  loses immediately to  21.Bxf7+ ! } 17. Bg5 { The most precise continuation.   17.Ng5 !?  deserves attention.  Bxg5  18.Bxg5  Rae8  19.Bd2  ± with a big advantage due to the bishop pair and superior piece coordination. } 17... Bxg5 { If  17...Rae8 ?  Black loses at once, in view of:  18.Bxe7  Rxe7  19.Rxe7  Qxe7  20.Re1  Qf6  21.Ng5  Qg6  22.Qxg6  hxg6  23.Nxf7 !  Black cannot recapture on f7 because 24. Re8+ wins the rook.   If  17...Bd6  the rook transfer decides the game after:  18.Re4  Ne5  19.Rh4  h6  20.Nxe5  Bxe5  21.Bxh6  +- } 18. Nxg5 h6 19. Re3 Na5 { The final mistake in a very difficult position.   The only defence was  19...Ne5  preventing  Qg6  , but after  20.Ne6 !  fxe6  21.Rxe5  ± White will be a full pawn up. } 20. Qg6 { +- Nice finish! } 20... hxg5 21. Rh3 Rfc8 { 21...Rfe8  does not help because of:  22.Rh7 !   but not  22.Qh7+ ?  Kf8  when the king escapes  22...Qe5   or  22...Kf8  23.Qxg7+  Ke7  24.Qxf7+  Kd6  25.Qxc7#  23.Qxf7+  Kxh7  24.Qh5# } 22. Re1 { Checkmate is unavoidable.   Final Remarks:  1. Black's position would have been much safer had he kept his knight on d5.   2. It is absolutely necessary to prevent, or at least prepare against, a possible d4-d5 break.   3. Black's biggest mistake was playing the weakening moves ...a7-a6 and ...b7-b5, wasting time and making the d4-d5 break even stronger.   4. After d4-d5 was played, the position was nearly lost and extremely difficult to conduct. } *

