{ @@HeaderStart@@Alexander Huzman - Levon Aronian, Plovdiv 2010@@HeaderEnd@@  Learning objective:  The break ...d5-d4  (colours reversed)  can be very strong, even in the form of a pawn sacrifice. } 1. Nf3 d5 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Bg5 Nbd7 6. cxd5 exd5 7. Qc2 c5 8. dxc5 h6 9. Bd2 O-O 10. a3 { This is a waste of time since Black was going to capture on c5 anyway.   Instead, theory suggests  10.e3  Bxc5  11.Rc1  Qe7  12.Be2  a6  13.Qd3  Nb6  14.O-O =  Carlsen-Ivanchuk, Romania 2011 } 10... Bxc5 11. e3 a6 12. Be2 b5 13. O-O Bb7 14. Rfd1 Rc8 15. Be1 Re8 16. Rac1 Nf8 { Black's knight is heading toward e6, in order to support the break ...d5-d4.   Somewhat stronger was  16...Nb6 !?  heading to the c4-square.  17.Nd4  Nc4  18.Bf3  Qe7  19.h3  Qe5  =+ Black is slightly better as the isolated d5-pawn is well supported, and he may create pressure on the centre and kingside with  ...Bd6  and  ...Ne4. } 17. Nd4 Qb6 18. Bf3 { It was necessary to support the d4-square.   Better was  18.Qd2  Ne6  19.Nxe6  Qxe6   or  19...fxe6 !?  20.Bf3  Bb6  with a standard isolani position.   20...Red8 !? =  The d5-pawn is immune to  21.Nxd5 ?  in view of  Rxc1  22.Nxf6+  Qxf6  23.Rxc1  Bxf3  24.gxf3  Qxf3  ∓ when Black regains the pawn favourably. } 18... Bxd4 19. Rxd4 { 19.exd4 ?  does not help, as  Ne6  20.Qd3  Nxd4 !  wins a pawn, since  21.Qxd4 ??  loses to  Rxe1+ !  22.Rxe1  Qxd4 } 19... Ne6 20. Rd2 { The option  20.Rdd1 ?!  does not solve White's problems either.  20...d4 !  21.Bxb7  Qxb7  22.exd4  Nf4  23.f3  N6d5  and Black is threatening  ...Nxc3  followed by  ...Ne2  or  ...Re2.  White is in deep trouble, for example:  24.Rd2  a5  25.Qb1  Nxc3  26.Rxc3  Rxc3  27.bxc3  Ne2+  28.Kh1  Nxc3  29.Qa1  b4  -+ The passed b-pawn, together with tactical threats on the first rank, make Black's initiative irresistible.   Instead  20.Rh4 !  (as suggested by Krasenkow)  allows White to stay in the game:  20...Rc4   The break  20...d4 ?!  is no longer effective, since after  21.Bxb7  Qxb7  22.exd4  the squares  e4  and  f4  are not available to Black's knights.   On the other hand  20...Red8 !?  =+ is a worthy alternative, preparing  ...d5-d4  and taking advantage of the misplaced rook on  h4  21.Rxc4  dxc4  =+ Black has some advantage owing to his superior piece coordination. } 20... d4 { Aronian decides to sacrifice his isolated pawn, activating all of his pieces; Black seizes an overwhelming initiative. } 21. Bxb7 { Much worse is  21.exd4 ?  Bxf3  22.gxf3  Nxd4  23.Qd1   or  23.Qd3  Nb3  -+  23...Rxe1+ !  -+ } 21... Qxb7 { of course not  21...dxc3 ?  due to:  22.Bxc8  cxd2  23.Bxd2  +- } 22. exd4 { Black is a pawn down, but now all his pieces collaborate in the attack. } 22... Ne4 23. Rdd1 { 23.Qxe4 ?  Qxe4  24.Nxe4  Rxc1  is also hopeless.   But a better defence was  23.f3  Nxd2  24.Qxd2  , though Black has a big advantage. } 23... Nf4 { -+ It is possible that Huzman allowed the ...d5-d4 sacrifice because he did not expect Black's knights to be so strong. Black is immediately threatening ...Nxc3, followed by ...Qxg2#. } 24. d5 { Blocking the a8-h1diagonal.   Black wins an exchange and the game after  24.f3  Nxc3  25.Bxc3  Ne2+  26.Kh1  Nxc1  27.Rxc1  a5 !  followed by  ...b5-b4. } 24... a5 { This strong moves enables a quick win.   Instead the tempting  24...Nxc3 ?!  is less precise, since after  25.Bxc3  Ne2+  26.Kh1  Nxc1  27.Qxc1  ∓ White's  d5  pawn allows him to hold for longer. } 25. Qb3 b4 26. axb4 axb4 { Threatening ...Nc5, followed by ...bxc3. } 27. Na2 { 27.Nxe4  does not help due to:  Rxc1  28.Rxc1  Ne2+  29.Kh1  Nxc1  -+ } 27... Ne2+ 28. Kh1 Nxc1 { Black wins the exchange and the rest is easy. } 29. Nxc1 Nf6 30. d6 { The try  30.Bxb4  is refuted by  30...Rb8  31.Na2  Nxd5 !  32.Qxd5   or  32.Rxd5 ?  Re1+  32...Qxd5  33.Rxd5  Rxb4 !  since  34.Nxb4 ?  Re1#  is mate. } 30... Qc6 31. Na2 Qxd6 32. Bxb4 { 32.Rxd6 ??  Rxe1# } 32... Qb6 33. f3 Qf2 { Final Remarks:   1. Time is essential to obtain a good piece set-up. White's imprecision with 10.a3 allowed Black to fight for an advantage from the start.   2. White's biggest mistake was not to reinforce his control of d4 with 18.Qd2, in which case the position would have been close to equal.   3. The ...d5-d4 pawn sacrifice gave Black an essentially winning initiative. } *

