{ @@HeaderStart@@Oleg Korneev - Rustam Kasimdzhanov, Melilla 2011@@HeaderEnd@@  Learning objectives:  1. This example reinforces the idea that having an isolani in the endgame is a big problem.   2. Black can use the weakness of the isolani to force the creation of new queenside weaknesses. } 1... c6 { White's main difficulty in this position is his lack of material denies him hope of counterplay. } 2. b4 { This move is necessary sooner or later in order to prevent ...c6-c5.   If White does not play b2-b4, then after  2.Kh2  Qd8  3.Qb4  Qd7  4.Qc4  Rd5  the threat of  ...c6-c5  forces White to play  5.b4  after all. } 2... Qd8 3. a3 h5 { Black improves his position as much as possible before going for decisive action. } 4. Qf4 g6 5. Qe5 Rd5 6. Qe4 Kg7 { Black brings the king closer to the centre, preparing himself for a rook endgame. } 7. Kg1 a5 { A typical break. Now that everything is ready, Black creates a new target in White's camp. White must choose between having a weak pawn on b4, or allowing ...c6-c5. } 8. Kh1 { Making things easier for Black, though the alternatives were not objectively better.   More stubborn was:  8.bxa5  But Black has good winning chances after:  c5 !   White has better prospects after  8...Qxa5  9.Rd3  Qd8  threatening  ...c6-c5  , and now:  10.Rb3 !  b5  11.Rb4  =+  9.Rd2   Searching for counterplay with  9.Rb1  cxd4  10.Rxb7  just barely fails against  10...d3  11.Qe6  d2   but not  11...Rf5 ?  12.Qd7 =  12.Qxf7+  Kh6  ∓ and Black is nearly winning, but I will not include any more lines as they are extremely long and quite irrelevant.  9...Qd7  Slowly preparing  ...Rxd4.   If  9...cxd4 ?!  10.Rd3  White has chances of holding  Hence White goes for:  10.Re2  cxd4  11.Rd2  d3  ∓ Although White's defence is very difficult to say the least. } 8... axb4 9. axb4 Qd6 { The b4-pawn is basically lost already. } 10. Qb1 Rb5 11. Qa1 Kh7 { More accurate was  11...f6 !  , heading for a queen endgame:  12.Rb1  Rxb4  13.Rxb4  Qxb4  14.Qa8  Qe1+  15.Kh2  Qe7  16.Kh1   Worse is  16.Qc8 ?  Qd6+  17.Kh1  b5  -+  16...Qd7  ∓ Black should win by pushing his b-pawn, though it requires good technique. } 12. Qa2 Kg8 13. Qa8+ Qf8 { Black heads into a favourable rook endgame, but misses a stronger option.   13...Kg7  14.Qa1  f6 !  would transpose into the variation  11...f6. } 14. Qxf8+ Kxf8 15. Rb1 Ke7 16. Kg1 Kd6 17. Kf2 Kd5 18. Ke3 Kc4 { Finally, the b4-pawn is lost. } 19. Ke4 { White misses a great defensive resource in  19.Rc1+ !  Kxb4  20.h4  The game is far from over, for example:  20...Ka5 !?  21.Ra1+  Kb6  22.Ra8  Rd5  ∓ White has a difficult defence ahead of him, but all is not yet lost. } 19... f5+ { Keeping control of the game.   If  19...Rxb4  then  20.Rc1+ !  Kb5  21.Ke5  , heading to  f6  in order to capture Black's kingside pawns. } 20. Kf4 Rxb4 21. Rc1+ Kxd4 { The rest is easy but instructive. } 22. Rd1+ Kc3+ 23. Kg5 Rd4 24. Rb1 Rd6 { This prevents any counterplay associated with Kxg6, and wins the game nicely. } 25. Rb6 { 25.Rxb7  does not help:  25...c5  will be followed by  ...c4  ,  ...Kd2  ,  ...c3-c2  winning. } 25... Kd4 26. g4 hxg4 27. hxg4 fxg4 28. fxg4 Kd5 29. Rxb7 c5 30. Kf4 c4 31. Ke3 c3 { Right on time! White can do nothing to stop the pawn. } 32. Rc7 { 32.Kd3 ?  loses to  32...Kc6+ } 32... Rc6 33. Rd7+ { The pawn endgame is lost after  33.Rxc6  Kxc6  34.Kd3  Kd5  35.Kxc3  Ke4 } 33... Ke5 34. Rd1 c2 35. Rc1 g5 36. Kd2 Kf4 37. Rf1+ { 37.Rg1  c1=Q+ !  and wins. } 37... Kxg4 38. Kc1 Rc5 { White cannot prevent the promotion of the g-pawn.   Final remarks   1. The standard plan ...Qd8 and ...Rd5 forces White to play b2-b4, in order to prevent ...c6-c5 winning a pawn.  2. Once b2-b4 had been played, the break ...a7-a5 forces the creation of a weak b4-pawn, or allows Black to finally achieve ...c6-c5.  3. The initial position looks like just a very slight advantage for Black, but in fact White lost the game almost without making a further mistake.  4. It should be noted that this version of the isolani is slightly different from previous examples, as Black had a pawn on the c-file, rather than the e-file. } *

