{ @@HeaderStart@@Short comment between games@@HeaderEnd@@  What would have happened if Black had the standard e-pawn instead of the c-pawn? The position is essentially the same, just replacing a c6-pawn with an e6-pawn, and again the threat of ...Qd8, ...Rd5 and ...e6-e5 is strong. In the previous game White had to play b2-b4. By analogy, in this position White should play: } 1. f4 Qd8 2. Kg1 h5 { Another plan is  2...Rd5  3.Qf2  Qd7  4.Rd2  f6  insisting on  ...e6-e5  to win the d4-pawn. After  5.Rd1  though, it is not so easy to break with  5...e5  due to  6.fxe5  fxe5  7.Rf1 !  Black must settle for a draw with  7...Qe7   but not  7...exd4 ?  due to  8.Qf8+  Kh7  9.Rf7  +-  8.dxe5  Rxe5 = } 3. Qb4 Qd7 4. Qc3 Rd5 5. Qd2 { Protecting the f4-pawn with  5.g3  creates further weaknesses, and can be met by  5...h4 !  6.g4  Rd6 !?  ∓ followed by  ...Rc6  and a dangerous penetration down the c-file, since White's king is very exposed. } 5... h4 { Preventing g2-g3. } 6. Qf2 Qd8 7. b3 Rf5 { followed by ...Qf6 or ...Qd6; White's defence will be difficult. In the next game, we will study how the isolani version present in the previous game could arise from the opening, and how a typical middlegame may develop. } *

