{ @@HeaderStart@@Etienne Bacrot - Romain Edouard, Caen 2011@@HeaderEnd@@  Learning objective:  This game illustrates kingside attacking chances in a standard isolani position. } 1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c4 dxc4 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 a6 6. O-O c5 7. Bb3 Nc6 8. Nc3 cxd4 9. exd4 Be7 10. Bg5 O-O 11. Qd2 Bd7 12. Rad1 { We have reached a standard position, and I should emphasize that great accuracy in calculation is needed to seize the initiative. } 12... Na5 { By pushing White's bishop away from b3, Black reduces the chances of a potential d4-d5 break.   The bishop cannot be chased away with  12...h6 ?  because of  13.Bxh6 !  gxh6  14.Qxh6  when Black is lost, in view of the threats  Ng5  and  Nce4  , or simply d4-d5 opening the lines for checkmate. An illustrative variation is:  Re8  15.d5  exd5   if  15...Bf8  16.Qg5+  +- White regains the piece with dividends  16.Nxd5  Nxd5  17.Bxd5  threatening  Qg6  and if  Bf5  18.Qh5 !  and wins.   The normal move  12...Rc8 ?!  is met by:  13.d5 !  exd5  14.Nxd5  Be6  15.Nxf6+  Bxf6  16.Bxe6  fxe6  17.Qe3  += } 13. Bc2 Nc4 14. Qe2 { Fighting for the initiative, Bacrot is willing to go into complications if necessary.   The passive  14.Qc1  gives Black a comfortable game:  Rc8  15.Rfe1  Re8 = } 14... Rc8 { This imprecision will cost Black the initiative.   Black should have accepted the challenge with:  14...Nxb2 !  15.Rc1 !?   15.Rb1  does not work owing to  15...Rc8 !  16.Rxb2  Rxc3  =+   15.Bxh7+  Nxh7  16.Bxe7  Qxe7  17.Qxb2  Rac8 =  15...Rc8  16.Ne5  The game is unclear, though chances are approximately level. } 15. Bb3 b5 { As Edouard points out, the key to White's 15th move is that  15...Na5 ?!  allows  16.d5 !  Now if  16...Nxb3 ?!   Instead  16...exd5  17.Bxd5  += When Black is under serious pressure.  17.d6  Na5  18.dxe7  Qxe7  19.Nd5 !  Black is nearly lost, for example  19...Qd8 ?   19...Qc5  20.b4  ±  20.Nxf6+  gxf6  21.Bh6  Re8  22.Ne5 !  +- threatening  Qg4+  then mate on  g7  , as well as  Rxd7.   After  15...Nb6  16.Ne5  += White may proceed with Rd3-h3 with a kingside attack. } 16. Ne5 Nb6 { If  16...Nxe5  17.dxe5  Ne8  18.Bxe7  Qxe7  19.Rd4  += White maintains an advantage by controlling the d-file. He may attempt an attack with  Qh5  and  Rh4  , or pressure the queenside with  Rfd1  and a2-a4. } 17. Rfe1 { The d4-d5 theme is still in the air, and this move supports it by creating indirect pressure against the bishop on e7. } 17... h6 { 17...b4 ?!  is met by  18.d5 !  This break proves effective once again:  18...exd5   worse is  18...bxc3 ?  19.dxe6  fxe6  20.Nxd7  Nbxd7  21.Bxe6+  Kh8  22.Bxd7  +-  19.Nxd7  Qxd7  20.Qxe7  Qxe7  21.Rxe7  bxc3  22.bxc3  Rxc3  23.Ra7  ± The endgame is very difficult for Black to hold. } 18. Bxh6 { White embarks on a very interesting piece sacrifice.   The option  18.Bh4  also deserves attention. Black does not have an easy way out of the pressure he is under, for example  18...Nfd5 ?!  attempting to trade pieces off, fails to:  19.Nxd5  Nxd5   19...Bxh4 ??  20.Nxb6  +-  20.Bxd5  Bxh4  21.Bb7  Rb8   or  21...Rc7  22.Bxa6  ±  22.Bc6 !  The key move.  22...Bc8   22...Bxc6 ?!  23.Nxc6  +-  23.d5 !  ± Opening the game when Black is not ready to respond effectively.   18.Bxf6  Generally, trading pieces does not help the side playing with an isolated pawn.  18...Bxf6  19.Qe4  Qe7  Black seems to be holding, though White's position remains slightly preferable. } 18... gxh6 { The intermediate move  18...b4 ?  fails to:  19.d5 !  exd5   19...bxc3 ?!  20.dxe6  fxe6  21.Nxd7  +-  20.Nxd5  Nfxd5  21.Bxd5  gxh6  22.Nxd7  Nxd7  23.Qxe7  +- } 19. Rd3 { The position is rather unclear, though approximately balanced.   As Edouard suggests, regaining the piece directly with  19.d5  exd5  20.Nxd7   20.Nxd5 ?  does not work due to  20...Nbxd5  21.Bxd5  Bb4 !  -+ followed by  Qe7  when White's attack is over  20...Qxd7  21.Qxe7  Qxe7  22.Rxe7  does not give an advantage to White, since after  22...Rfd8  Black obtains sufficient counterplay with  ...Nc4. } 19... Kh8 { An interesting variation is  19...b4 !?  20.Rg3+  Kh8  21.Bc2  when White has a nice attack, for example:  21...bxc3   21...Nc4 !?  ∞ gives a better fight  22.Qe3  Ng8  23.Rxg8+  Kxg8  24.Qxh6  f5  25.Re4 !!  +- Threatening  Rg4+  winning; the rook is untouchable, as after  25...fxe4 ?  26.Qg6+  Kh8  27.Bxe4  , checkmate is unstoppable. } 20. Qd2 { It was possible to regain the piece immediately with  20.d5  exd5  21.Nxd7  Qxd7   instead  21...Nbxd7  22.Nxd5  Nxd5  23.Rxd5  yields a dangerous initiative  22.Qxe7  Qxe7  23.Rxe7  with a slightly better endgame for White. } 20... Ng8 21. d5 Nc4 { Another option was  21...exd5  which leads to a forced line:  22.Nxd5  Nc4  23.Qc3  Nxe5  24.Qxe5+  Bf6  25.Nxf6  Nxf6  26.Red1  Re8  27.Rxd7  Qxd7  28.Qxf6+  Kh7  29.g3 !?  when the position is dynamically balanced. } 22. Bxc4 bxc4 23. Rd4 Bc5 { A blunder in time trouble.   It was difficult to find the only move  23...Qe8 !  after which White has plenty of choices leading to unclear play, for example  24.Ne4 !?  when White maintains many potential threats, and has enough compensation for the piece. } 24. dxe6 { White is just winning now. } 24... Bxd4 25. Qxd4 Qf6 { 25...Bxe6 ?  26.Nxf7+  wins Black's queen. } 26. exd7 Rcd8 27. Re3 { White wants to push Black's queen away from the a1-h8 diagonal. } 27... Ne7 28. Rf3 Nc6 29. Nxf7+ { 29.Nxf7+  The endgame is lost after  29...Rxf7  30.Qxf6+  Rxf6  31.Rxf6  and White comes out with at least three extra pawns.  Final remarks  1. The break d4-d5 was a predominant theme in this game; which prevented many of Black's desired moves.  2. The alternative 18.Bh4 would have given a pleasent, slow-paced but steady advantage.  3. Although the piece sacrifice 18.Bxh6 only gives equality, it is justified in practice, as White's attack was far easier to play than Black's defence. In many crucial variations Black was forced to find a series of only moves in order to survive. } *

