{ @@HeaderStart@@Magnus Carlsen - Wang Yue, Linares 2009@@HeaderEnd@@  Learning objective:  In contrast to the previous game, the player who has an isolani can obtain good counterplay if he possesses his good bishop. This is true despite already having traded two minor pieces. } 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e3 a6 5. Nf3 b5 6. b3 Bg4 7. Bd2 Nbd7 8. h3 Bxf3 9. Qxf3 b4 10. Na4 e5 { Black correctly converts the game into an isolani battle where he will have enough counterplay. Notice how far White's knight is from the ideal d4-square.   Instead  10...e6  11.Bd3  a5  12.Rc1  Bd6  13.O-O  O-O  14.cxd5  cxd5  15.Rc6  += gives White a pleasingly dominating position with little black counterplay. } 11. Rc1 Bd6 12. cxd5 cxd5 13. dxe5 Nxe5 14. Qd1 O-O 15. Be2 a5 { We have reached the position of interest, where White has the pair of bishops and a healthy pawn structure. Black needs to arrange his pieces well in order to achieve good counterplay. } 16. Rc2 Qe7 17. Bc1 { By following up with Bb2, White wants to improve his bishop, as it was useless on d2.   Castling first with  17.O-O  Rad8  is likely to transpose to the game, as White will have to play  Bc1  sooner or later. } 17... Rad8 18. Bb2 Ng6 19. O-O Ne4 20. Bd4 { This blockades the d5-pawn and prepares Bb6 pressuring Black's queenside. } 20... Nh4 { Black's knights are ideally placed on e4 and h4, pressuring the kingside and inviting White to weaken his position. Black has full compensation for his isolated pawn. } 21. Bd3 { If White simply intends to grab some material with:  21.Bb6  Black can give up an exchange for activity with:  21...Bb8 !?   21...Qg5 !?  also deserves attention.  22.Bxd8   White must accept the challenge, otherwise  ...Rd6  will follow:  22.Kh1 ?  Rd6  ∓ with a dangerous attack.  22...Rxd8  Here Black has enough threats to compensate for the exchange sacrifice, say after:  23.Bd3   Or  23.Qc1  Qd6  24.f4  Ba7 !  and White is tied up:  25.Bd3   25.Rc8 ?  Bxe3+ !  -+  25...Nf5  26.Rf3  Nxe3  27.Rxe3  Qxf4  28.Rce2  f5 !  This curious position is dynamically balanced, for example  29.Bxe4  fxe4  30.Kh1  Rf8  31.Qe1  Rc8  ∞ when it is unclear how White may release his pieces.  23...Qd6  24.f4   But not  24.g3 ?  Nxg3 !  ∓  24...Nf5  25.Bxe4  Nxe3  26.Bxh7+  Kxh7  27.Qd3+  Qg6  28.Qxg6+  fxg6 = } 21... Nf5 { Black wants to get rid of White's strong bishop on d4.   Worthy of consideration is  21...Bb8 !?  with kingside threats, such as  ...Qd6  or  ...f7-f5-f4  , e.g.  22.Re1  f5  23.f4  g5 !  ⇆ with a dangerous kingside initiative.   21...Qg5 ?  is simply answered by  22.Qg4 !  when Black is nearly lost after  22...Qxg4   or  22...Qh6  23.Bxg7 !  Qxg7  24.Qxh4  ±  23.hxg4  ± as the pawns on  a5  and  d5  are very weak. } 22. Bb6 Rb8 23. Bxe4 { The materialistic  23.Bxa5 ?!  runs into tactical problems with  23...Nxf2 !  24.Rfxf2  Nxe3  25.Bxh7+  Kxh7  26.Qd3+  Kg8  when Black's position is preferable, owing to his superior piece coordination.   Better was  23.Qf3  g6  24.Rfc1  Qe5  25.g3  h5  aiming for  ...h5-h4  26.h4 !  += Now Black's counterplay is reasonably under control, therefore White's position is slightly preferable. } 23... Qxe4 { White gave up the pair of bishops to trade off Black's powerful knight, but the counterplay still persists. } 24. Rd2 { If  24.Qe2  Nh4  25.f3  Qg6  Black remains threatening, for example  26.f4  Nf5  27.Qd3  Rxb6 !  28.Nxb6  Nxe3 !  regaining the exchange:  29.Qxg6  fxg6  30.Rc6  Nxf1  31.Rxd6  Ng3  with level chances. } 24... Rxb6 25. Nxb6 Qe5 { As Giri points out, Black can force a draw with:  25...Nxe3  26.fxe3  Qxe3+  27.Rdf2  Qg3   another option was  27...Qxb6  28.Kh1  Qe3  29.Qf3  Qe5  30.g3 =  28.Re2  Qh2+  29.Kf2  Qg3+ = } 26. Re1 { White commits a serious mistake.   The only defence was  26.g3  Nxg3  27.Nxd5  Nxf1   or  27...Ne2+ !?  28.Kg2  Qg5+  29.Kf3  Qh5+  30.Kg2  Qg5+ =  28.Kxf1  Rd8  when the position is approximately equal. } 26... Qh2+ 27. Kf1 Qh1+ 28. Ke2 Qxg2 { Black's attack is far more important than being an exchange down. } 29. Rxd5 { Another mistake in a difficult position.   The only defence was the computer-like move  29.Kd3 !  after which  29...Nh4  30.Qg4 !  Nf3  31.Ke2   the queen cannot be taken with  31.Qxg2 ??  because of  31...Nxe1+  32.Ke2  Nxg2  -+  31...Qxg4  32.hxg4  Nxd2  33.Kxd2  f5 !  ∓ and Black will have very good winning chances by pushing his h-pawn. } 29... Ng3+ 30. Kd3 Bc7 { White is an exchange up, but this is definitely not enough compensation for the exposure of the white king. The position is technically won for Black, and the rest of the game is quite unrelated to the topic of this chapter, but I include it since I believe it is just a fun game to watch. } 31. fxg3 Bxb6 32. Kc4 Rb8 { Anticipating White's king will go to b5; the threat is ...Qe4 followed by a discovered check. } 33. Kb5 { No better was  33.e4  Qxg3  followed by  ...Qc7  or  ...Qxh3  winning. } 33... Bd4+ { An understandable human imprecision.   The computer move  33...Bd8+ !!  wins right away, for example:  34.Kc6   34.Ka4 ??  Qxa2#  34...Qe4  35.Qd4  Qe6+  36.Rd6  Qc8+  37.Kd5  Rb5+  38.Ke4  Qf5# } 34. Kc4 Bf6 { Better was  34...Bb6 !  hoping for another chance to find  ...Bd8+  !!. } 35. Qd3 Qxg3 36. Rd1 Qc7+ 37. Rc5 Qb7 38. Qd6 { A better defence was  38.Qd7 ! } 38... Qe4+ 39. Rd4 Qc2+ 40. Kd5 Qg2+ 41. e4 Rd8 { Finally the game becomes clear and the rest is easy for Black, owing to the extra pawns and White's exposed king. } 42. Qxd8+ Bxd8 43. Rc8 g6 44. Rxd8+ Kg7 45. Rd3 Qc2 46. Kd4 a4 47. bxa4 Qxa2 48. Kc5 b3 49. Rb8 b2 50. Rdb3 Qxa4 51. Rxb2 Qxe4 52. R8b3 Kh6 53. Rc3 f5 54. Rbb3 Qe5+ 55. Kc4 Kh5 56. Kd3 Kh4 57. Kd2 f4 58. Rf3 g5 59. Rfd3 Qc5 60. Rbc3 Qf2+ 61. Kd1 Qf1+ 62. Kd2 Qg2+ 63. Kd1 Qe4 64. Kd2 h5 { Final remarks  1. Black's decision to accept an isolani was based on two main factors: White's knight would not be useful in an isolani position; Black was rid of his bad bishop and had a good bishop to create critical threats down the b8-h2 diagonal.   2. 