 Ne4 !  =+ controlling key central squares such as  c5  21...Ng4  22.Rh5  Nf6  23.Rh4  += with interesting attacking chances on the kingside. } 20... Nh4 { If  20...Nxe5  21.Rxe5  h6  22.a4  += White is better due to his space, the pair of bishops and Black's lack of active plans. } 21. Bd3 { It was more important to activate the rook with the accurate  21.Rad1 !  preparing a d4-d5 break against Black's potential ...Nh5; after  21...h6   or  21...Nd7  22.Ng4  += with attacking chances on the kingside.   21...Nh5 ?!  is met by  22.d5 !  ±  22.Qe3  += with a good and flexible position. } 21... Nd7 { Instead  21...Nh5 !  would allow Black to gain counterplay on the kingside, for example  22.Rad1 ?   Or if  22.Bf1  f6  23.Ng4  Nf4   Therefore it is necessary to give up the pair of bishops with:  22.Be4  Nf4  23.Bxa8  Rxa8  24.g3  Nh3+  25.Kf1  f6 !?  ∞  is met by  22...f6 !  and now Black wins material after:  23.Ng4  Nf4  24.Bf1  Nh3+ !  25.Kh1  h5  26.Ne3  Nf2+  27.Kg1  Nxd1  -+ } 22. Nxd7 Rxd7 { This move is a mistake as Black is no longer able to prevent the d4-d5 break.   More stubborn was  22...Qxd7  23.Qc2  h6  24.Qf2  Nf5  25.Bxf5  exf5  26.d5  f6  27.Qd4  += though White enjoys a central passed pawn. } 23. Qc2 Kh8 { The optimistic  23...Bxf3 ?!  fails due to  24.Qf2   or  24.Bxh7+ !  24...Nxg2  25.Qxf3  Nxe1  26.Rxe1  ± when two bishops are far stronger than a rook and two pawns in this open game.   Safer was  23...Ng6  24.d5  Red8  25.Qc3  f6   but not  25...e5 ?  due to  26.Bf5   or  26.Bxg6 !?  ± winning a pawn  26...Re7  27.a4  preventing  ...b6-b5  , and now  27...Nh4  28.Be4  Ree8  29.Rac1  ± gives White a dominating position  26.Bxg6  hxg6  27.Rxe6  b5  28.cxb5  Bxd5  29.Qxc7  Rxc7  30.Re2  += Black has drawing chances due to the opposite-coloured bishops. } 24. Qf2 { An interesting option was  24.d5 !  immediately developing an attack.   but not  24.Bxh7 ?  due to  24...f5 !  and the bishop is lost. } 24... Qd8 { In the event of  24...Ng6  25.a4  ± White can prepare and threaten with either break, a4-a5 or d4-d5.   The immediate break  25.d5 !?  is interesting too:  25...Rdd8  26.Qe3 !?   preventing  26...exd5  and now  26...Qf4   while  26...e5  loses after  27.Bxg6 !  fxg6   even worse is  27...hxg6 ?  28.Bxe5  Qd7  29.Qh6+ !  28.Rac1  followed by  Bxe5.  27.Bxg6  Qxe3+  28.Rxe3  hxg6  29.Rae1  += gives White a favourable endgame. } 25. d5 { This well-prepared d4-d5 break is simply winning for White. Black cannot defend against such a strong initiative, especially since his pieces lack coordination and White possesses the bishop pair. } 25... b5 { 25...exd5 ?  loses to  26.Qxh4 !  winning a piece since  26...Rxe1+  27.Rxe1  Qxh4 ?  28.Re8#  is the end. } 26. Bc2 Rg8 { More stubborn was  26...bxc4  though after  27.Ba4  Nf5   even worse is  27...Bxd5 ?  28.Bxd7  Qxd7  29.Qxh4  +-  28.Bxd7  Qxd7  29.dxe6  fxe6  30.Be5  Black is technically lost. } 27. dxe6 fxe6 { 27...Rd2  28.Re2  Rxe2  29.Qxe2  fxe6  30.cxb5  and White wins. } 28. Rad1 { A simple yet beautiful move which illustrates White's overwhelming initiative once d4-d5 is achieved. Black has no hope of dealing with the multiple threats, the most direct being Rxd7 followed by Qxh4.   The imprecise  28.Rxe6 ?  is met by  28...Rd2 !  29.Re2  Rxe2  30.Qxe2  Qg5  (threatening ...Bxf3)  31.Rf1  bxc4  ± when Black is holding the game for longer. } 28... Rxd1 29. Rxd1 Qg5 30. Qg3 { Nice move! It forces Black to choose between a lost endgame and allowing a mating attack. } 30... Qe7 { Or  30...Qxg3  31.hxg3  Ng6  32.cxb5  winning due to the bishop pair, the initiative and the extra pawn. } 31. Rd7 { Black resigned, in view of  31...Qxd7  32.Qxh4  and there is no satisfactory way to prevent  Qxh7#.  Final remarks  1. It was not possible for Black just to break the hanging pawns with 16...e5. White's good piece placement rendered this move ineffective.  2. White's pair of bishops played a central role in many positions. They are very helpful in an open position such a