{ @@HeaderStart@@Axel Bachmann - Max Cornejo, Asuncion 2009@@HeaderEnd@@  Learning objective:  This game illustrates how the break b3-b4 can be successfully carried out against the hanging pawns. } 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 c5 3. Bg2 Nc6 4. d4 Nf6 5. O-O e6 6. b3 Be7 7. Bb2 O-O 8. Nbd2 b6 9. dxc5 bxc5 10. c4 Bb7 11. cxd5 exd5 12. Rc1 Qa5 13. a3 Rad8 14. Qc2 h6 15. Rfd1 Qb6 16. e3 { After a relatively normal opening we arrive at the position we are interested in. } 16... Nd7 { Preventing Nh4-f4, and supporting the c5-pawn.   Another option was  16...Rfe8  17.Ne1   The idea  17.Nh4  is met by  17...Ng4  18.Nf5  Bf8  19.h3  Nge5 =  17...Nb8  18.Nd3  Nbd7   18...Rc8 ?  fails to  19.Bxf6 !  Bxf6  20.Nxc5  ±  19.b4 !  += White obtains good chances by breaking up the hanging pawns. } 17. Qf5 { The d5-pawn is not really threatened by this move.   The alternative was:  17.e4 !?  d4   or  17...dxe4  18.Nxe4  Na5  19.Nfd2  +=  18.Nc4  Qc7  19.b4 !?  Breaking the c5-d4 chain.  cxb4  20.Nxd4  Nxd4  21.Bxd4  bxa3  22.Nxa3  Qxc2  23.Nxc2  Bc5  24.Ne3  += White is better, though the limited material offers drawing chances to Black.   At this moment the transfer  17.Ne1  aiming for Ne1-d3 pressuring the c5-pawn, can be met by  17...Nce5  18.Nd3  Nxd3  19.Qxd3  Rfe8  with a level game. } 17... Na5 { Heading in the wrong direction. Placing a knight on a5 only gives more strength to the typical b3-b4 break.   Better was  17...Rfe8  18.Qg4   but not  18.Qxd5 ??  Nde5  19.Qe4  Nd3  ∓  20.Rb1 ?  Nd4 !  -+  18...Bf6  with level chances. } 18. Rb1 { A worthy alternative was:  18.b4 !?  Nc6   or  18...cxb4  19.axb4  Bxb4  20.Qg4  with a dangerous kingside initiative  19.Qg4  g6   19...Bf6  20.Bxf6  Nxf6  21.bxc5  ±  20.Qf4  Kh7  21.e4 !  ± White has pushed both typical breaks b3-b4 and e3-e4, with great tactical chances. } 18... Nf6 { If  18...Nc6  the break  19.b4 !?  deserves attention, for example:  19...cxb4  20.axb4  Nxb4  21.Qg4  g6  22.Bd4 !?  += with more than sufficient compensation. } 19. Qc2 { This is somewhat overcautious.   The immediate  19.b4 !  was again very strong:  19...cxb4   or  19...Bc8  20.Qc2 !  ± is similar to the main line  20.axb4  Nc4   20...Bxb4 ?  loses to  21.Bxf6 !  gxf6  22.Qg4+  Kh7  23.Qxb4  21.Bd4  ± With good control of the centre. } 19... Bc8 20. Nh4 Qe6 21. b4 { Finally White decides to break with b3-b4. This will turn the hanging pawns c5/d5 into a weak isolated d5-pawn. Also, the d4-square becomes available for a knight. } 21... Nb7 { The knight will not come back into the game.   The lesser evil was:  21...cxb4  22.axb4  Nc6   22...Bxb4 ??  loses a piece to  23.Bxf6  23.b5  Nb4  24.Qb3  a5  25.Ra1  Qb6  26.Bf1  += Black has a difficult position due to the weak a5- and d5-pawns. } 22. Nhf3 { This move maintains the pressure, but misses a stronger continuation.   The most precise was:  22.Nb3 !  In order to create serious threats on the kingside with Nd4-f5. After  22...c4   or  22...cxb4  23.axb4  ± followed by the strong Nd4-f5 or Nd4-c6  23.Nd4  Qb6  24.Ndf5  Black cannot avoid material loss, for example:  24...Rfe8  25.Bd4  Qe6  26.Qb2  Nd6  27.Nxe7+  Qxe7  28.Bxf6  Qxf6  29.Qxf6  gxf6  30.Rxd5  +- } 22... Ne4 { Accepting a broken pawn structure which will be severely punished.   A better defence was  22...Rfe8  23.bxc5  Nxc5  24.Nd4  += though White has a very favourable version of the isolani. } 23. Nxe4 dxe4 24. Ne5 { White has wonderful central control and will soon gain material. } 24... cxb4 { The lesser evil was:  24...Bf6  25.Qxe4  Rfe8  26.Rxd8  Nxd8  27.f4  ± } 25. axb4 Rxd1+ { Or  25...Bxb4  26.Nc6 !  Rxd1+  27.Rxd1  a5  28.Bxe4  with winning threats, for example  28...Nd6  29.Bd5  Qg4  30.Rd4 } 26. Rxd1 f5 { Supporting the e4-pawn, but creating more weaknesses.   If  26...Bxb4  27.Nc6  Bd6  28.Bxe4  and White wins.   or  26...Nd6  27.Nc6   but not  27.Bxe4 ?  Nxe4  28.Qxe4  f6  -+  27...Bf6  28.Nxa7  when the b-pawn decides the game. } 27. Bf1 { Black's position is hopeless due to his poor piece coordination and the severity of his weaknesses. } 27... Kh7 28. Nc6 Bd6 29. Nxa7 Bd7 30. Qc3 Qg6 { 30...Qe7  31.b5  +- } 31. Ba6 { Now Black loses a piece by force. } 31... f4 { 31...Rb8  32.Bxb7  Rxb7  33.Rxd6 !  Qxd6 ?  34.Qxg7# } 32. exf4 { Final remarks  1. Black's pieces were not very well arranged to start with. On move 17, it would have been better to have a knight on d7 rather than c6, and a bishop on e6 rather than b7.   2. White had multiple opportunities to break up the centre with b3-b4, all of which worked well due to his well-coordinated forces.   3. After the b3-b4 break the essence of the advantage is based on White's pieces using the d4-square as a pivot toward the creation of threats. } *

