{ @@HeaderStart@@Bartlomiej Macieja - Holden Hernandez, Mexico City 2012@@HeaderEnd@@  Learning objectives:  1. Black's imprecise opening play allows the hanging pawns to be blocked ideally.   2. We then learn how White may use this fact to disrupt the centre with the standard e3-e4 break, gaining a big advantage. } 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 a5 5. g3 d5 6. Qc2 c5 7. cxd5 cxd4 8. Bg2 O-O 9. Nxd4 Qb6 10. e3 exd5 11. O-O Nc6 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. Rc1 { I was surprised to find eight games at the GM-level with this position. Black experiences serious difficulties due to his inability to achieve the ...c6-c5 advance in time. } 13... Bxd2 { Accelerating White's plans. The first objective will be to control c5 with Nb3-c5.   More accurate is  13...Bd7  but it does not quite solve Black's problems after:  14.Bc3  Be7   or  14...Bxc3  15.Nxc3  Rfb8  16.Na4  Qa7  17.b3  += and White has a lasting advantage due to the blockade on  c5  15.Bd4  Qb7  16.Nc3  Rfb8   16...c5 ?  17.Bxf6  Bxf6  18.Nxd5  +-  17.Na4  ± This is a position to remember. The blockade  Bd4  ,  Nc5  turns the c6/d5 pawns into serious weaknesses. Black has no chance to carry out any of the typical plans in a hanging pawns position. } 14. Nxd2 Bd7 15. Nb3 Rfb8 16. Nc5 Be8 { The capture  16...Qxb2  does not solve the problems after  17.Nxd7  Nxd7   17...Qxc2 ??  18.Nxf6+  ±  18.Qxc6  Nf6  19.Bxd5  Nxd5  20.Qxd5  ± when White has good chances of winning this endgame. } 17. b3 Qa7 { White has blocked the central pawns and his pieces dominate the board. Hence, it is a good moment for the central break: } 18. e4 { Permanently damaging the hanging pawns. } 18... h6 { This allows White to rearrange his pieces.   The best defence was  18...Rb5  += preventing the transfer Rc1-e1 followed by Ra1-c1. } 19. Re1 dxe4 20. Bxe4 Rb5 21. Rac1 Nxe4 22. Rxe4 { With a big positional advantage which soon turns into a kingside attack. } 22... f6 23. Qc3 Bf7 24. Qe3 Qb8 25. Re7 Qf8 { Now White could decide the game immediately with: } 26. a4 { Instead, White played  26.Re1 ?  Rbb8  27.Nd7  Qxe7 !  28.Qxe7  Re8  29.Qxe8+  Bxe8  30.Nc5  += and eventually won the endgame. } 26... Rb4 { 26...Rbb8  also loses to  27.Nd7 } 27. Nd7 Qd8 28. Rd1 { Threatening Nxf6+ followed by Rxd8. The key to 26.a4 ! is that now Black does not have 28...Rd5 available. } 28... Bd5 { 28...Qc8  loses to  29.Nb6  Rxb6  30.Qxb6 } 29. Rxd5 cxd5 30. Nxf6+ Kh8 { 30...Kf8  31.Qe6  Qxe7   31...gxf6  32.Qf7#  32.Qg8# } 31. Qxh6+ gxh6 32. Rh7# { Final remarks  1. Black's opening needs improvement. The hanging pawns will always be inferior if they can readily be blocked as in this game.   2. The break e3-e4 not only forced Black to accept a weak and isolated c6-pawn, but also opened lines for White's attack. } *

