{ @@HeaderStart@@Vladimir Akopian - Alexandr Schimanov, Plovdiv 2012@@HeaderEnd@@  Learning objective:  This game is an example of White's chances of a mating attack. } 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nd7 5. Ng5 Ngf6 6. Bd3 e6 7. N1f3 Bd6 8. Qe2 h6 9. Ne4 Nxe4 10. Qxe4 Qc7 11. O-O Nf6 { An imprecision.   Theory suggests  11...b6  12.Qg4  Kf8  13.b3  Bb7  14.Bb2  Nf6  15.Qh3  Nd5  with an approximately balanced game. } 12. Qh4 b6 13. Bg5 { White has a better position due to his lead in development, extra space and attacking prospects against Black's uncastled king.   The inaccurate  13.Re1  Bb7  14.Ne5   14.Bg5 !?  is met by  14...O-O-O ! =  when Black's king is safe on the queenside. } 13... Be7 { 13...Nd5  is no better, due to  14.c4  Nb4  15.Bb1  += when Black's knight on  b4  is doing nothing. } 14. Bf4 { After  14.Rad1 !?  Black can trade off bishops with  14...Nd5  15.Bxe7  Qxe7  16.Qg3  O-O  17.c4  Nf6  18.Rfe1  += but White maintains a preferable position due to his space advantage. } 14... Qd8 { Inaccurate; Black does not quite realize how dangerous White's threats really are.   14...Nd5 !  is necessary:  15.Bxc7  Bxh4  But here White has several options to maintain a small advantage, for example:  16.Be5 !?   a worthy alternative is  16.Bxb6  Bxf2+  17.Rxf2  axb6  18.Ne5  f6 !  19.Ng6  +=  16...Bf6  17.Rfd1  Black cannot easily release his position, for example  17...Bb7  hoping for  ...c6-c5  next move:  18.c4  Ne7  19.c5 !?  += Keeping Black's light-squared bishop out of the game for a while. } 15. Ne5 { A few precise moves have been enough for White to dominate the board; Black is already on the verge of losing. } 15... Bb7 { It is too late for simplification by  15...Nd5 ?  16.Qg4  Nxf4  17.Qxf4  O-O  18.Nxc6  as Black simply loses a pawn.   A better defence is  15...Nd7  16.Qg3  Nxe5   16...O-O ??  17.Bxh6  +-  17.dxe5   or  17.Bxe5  Bf6  18.Rae1  ± but Black can hold on for longer  17...Kf8  18.Rad1  ± and White is much better, but he does not have an obvious route to victory. } 16. Rad1 { The black monarch is trapped in the centre, thus placing rooks on the d- and e-files is simply logical. } 16... Bd6 { This is probably Black's last inaccuracy.   Black cannot escape the centre with  16...O-O ?  since  17.Bxh6 !  just wins, for example:  17...gxh6  18.Qxh6  (the threat is Ng4 followed by Nxf6 and mate on h7)  18...Re8  19.Bg6 !  fxg6   or  19...Rf8  20.Rd3  and mate is unstoppable  20.Qxg6+  Kh8  21.Nf7#   It is not too late for  16...Nd7  17.Qg3  Nxe5  18.dxe5  g5 !?  when Black gets to survive longer, though White is indisputably better. } 17. Rfe1 Qe7 { Again  17...O-O ?  loses to  18.Bxh6  gxh6  19.Qxh6  followed by Re3-g3.   An alternative is  17...Bxe5  18.Bxe5  O-O  though after  19.Qh3 !  the threat of Re3-g3 wins. } 18. Qh3 { Creating the nasty threat of 19.Ng6 ! fxg6 20.Rxe6. } 18... Nd5 19. Bg3 O-O { Trying to escape to the queenside with  19...O-O-O  fails to:  20.Ng6 !  fxg6   20...Qc7  21.Nxh8  +-  21.Rxe6  Qd7  22.Bxd6  +-   19...Nf6  20.Ng6 !  fxg6  21.Rxe6  and wins. } 20. c4 { Black's position is desperate. } 20... Nf6 { 20...Bxe5  doesn't help as after  21.Bxe5  Nf6  22.Re3  the entrance of the rook into the attack decides the game:  Rfd8  23.Rf3  Nd7  24.Bf4  (threatening Bxh6)  24...f5  25.Rg3  Kh7  26.Re1 !  Followed by  Bxf5  or  Rxe6  winning.   Neither does  20...Nb4  achieve anything:  21.Bb1  and Black is defenceless, for example  21...Rfe8  22.a3  Na6  23.c5  Bc7  24.Bh4  f6  25.Bg6  with a crushing attack. } 21. Bh4 { Threatening Ng4 followed by Bxf6 winning. } 21... g5 22. Bxg5 hxg5 23. Qh6 { Black resigns since mate cannot be avoided without great material loss.   For example:  23.Qh6  Rfd8  24.Ng4 !  Nxg4  25.Qh7+  Kf8  26.Qh8#  Final remarks  1. White's attack became irresistible after Black fell behind in development. The sacrifice Bxh6 is a recurring idea in this structure.  2. Black's best attempt for a defence was playing ...Nd7xe5 hoping White would play dxe5. In many variations, such a change of structure would block many lines of attack allowing Black to survive longer. } *

