{ @@HeaderStart@@Ivan Ivanisevic - Pero Ascic, Zupanja 2007@@HeaderEnd@@  Learning objective:  This game is an example of the advance c4-c5, in order to gain control of the d6-square and to fix the centre, also preventing Black from releasing his position with ...c6-c5. } 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c6 { The Catalan main line is   3...Nf6  4.g3  Be7  5.Bg2  O-O  6.O-O  dxc4  when Black should have a perfectly playable position. } 4. g3 Nd7 5. Bg2 Bd6 6. O-O Ngf6 7. Nc3 O-O { Black has developed his pieces schematically with little regard to specific move orders. In particular, we should note that Black's bishop is hanging on d6, hence the reply: } 8. Nd2 { Simply logical, and creating difficulties for Black. White will play e3-e4 next move and recapture with Nxe4 gaining a crucial tempo. } 8... Re8 { In the event of   8...Bc7  9.e4  dxc4  or   9...dxe4  10.Ndxe4  Nxe4  11.Nxe4  since  e5 ?  is met by  12.d5 !  ±  with a strong passed pawn.  10.e5  Nd5  11.Nxc4  +=  White is better. This is similar to the fragment of Andreikin - Kramnik which will be analyzed in the next chapter. } 9. e4 dxe4 10. Ndxe4 Nxe4 { After   10...Bc7  11.Re1  h6  12.f4  Nxe4  13.Nxe4  Rb8  14.Be3  a5  15.Qc2  b6  16.Rad1  +=  as in the game Papaioannou - Lajthajm, Budva 2009, White dominates the board since neither ... e6-e5 nor ...c6-c5 is possible. } 11. Nxe4 Be7 { Giving up the b8-h2 diagonal and admitting 6... Bd6 was imprecise.  A healthier continuation is   11...Bc7  preventing 12. Bf4, though after  12.Bg5  f6  13.Be3  +=  White enjoys a pleasent spatial advantage. } 12. Bf4 { The best move, keeping an eye on the ...e6-e5 break.  Instead, the premature   12.c5 ?!  would allow  e5 !  after which Black solves most of his problems, for example  13.Be3  exd4  14.Bxd4  Nf6  15.Bxf6  Qxd1  16.Rfxd1  Bxf6  17.Nxf6+  gxf6  with an inferior but defensible position. } 12... Nf6 { Black is not well prepared for   12...c5 ?  since after  13.dxc5  Nxc5  14.Nd6 !  White wins the pair of bishops and the queenside majority will advance easily, for example:  Bxd6  15.Bxd6  Qb6  16.Qd4  Nd7  17.c5  Qa6  18.a4 !  and White wins after either  Nf6  or   18...e5  19.Rfe1  19.b4 } 13. c5 { As a young chess player I was very puzzled by moves like this. My strategy books had taught me that c4-c5 was a colossal positional mistake since the d4-pawn would be permanently vulnerable as a backward pawn, and the d5-square would be easily controlled by Black's knight. This is all true, but in this pawn structure the c4-c5 move has far more benefits than drawbacks. This move fixes the central structure, permanently banning the ...c6-c5 break and locking in Black's light-squared bishop. In addition, the d6-square becomes accessible to a knight, and clearly White's knight on d6 would be far more powerful than Black's knight on d5. Finally, White secures a stable spatial advantage, and the d4-pawn is easily defended in the current position, though it could become vulnerable if White did not proceed correctly. } 13... Nd5 { Black not helped by:   13...Nxe4  14.Bxe4  Bf6  Or   14...Qd7  15.Be5  ±  since  f6 ?!  is met by  16.Qh5 !   14...f5  15.Bg2  Bf6  16.Be5  Qe7  17.Qc2  ±  15.Be5  White controls the board, for example:  g6  Even worse is   15...Bxe5  16.dxe5  f5  or   16...Bd7  17.Qc2 !  h6  18.Rad1  +-  17.Bg2  Rf8  18.Qc2  Qc7  19.f4  Rd8  20.Rad1  ±  and White is already close to winning.  16.Qc2  Qe7  17.Rad1  White has a free hand in this position, hence he can slowly improve, gain space, or create an attack, for example:  Bg7  18.Rd3  Rd8  19.Rfd1  Bd7  20.Qc3  Threatening Bxg7 followed by d4-d5.  Bf8  21.h4 !?  ± } 14. Bd6 { By trading dark-squared bishops White takes possession of the d6-square. } 14... b6 { This move does not help to create counterplay, but it does turn the c6-pawn into a new target.  If   14...Bxd6  15.Nxd6  Re7  16.Re1  White is in full control, and possibly the best continuation is:  Nf6  17.Qd2  Rd7  18.Rad1  Rxd6  conserving material by   18...Ne8  leads to  19.Nc4  Qc7  20.b4  Nf6  21.a4  Rd8  22.b5  ±  - a typical plan to create pressure against the c6-pawn; White is close to winning  19.cxd6  Qxd6  20.Qa5  ±  Black is unlikely to survive an exchange down. } 15. Qa4 b5 { This move is basically accepting a lost position. The inclusion of the moves 14... b6 and 15... b5 only turned the c6-pawn into a chronic weakness.  Slightly better is   15...Qd7  keeping the tension, though after  16.Rac1  Rd8  17.Bxe7  Nxe7  18.Nd6  only White is able to create threats, for example  a5  19.Rfe1  Rb8  20.Qc2  Ba6  21.Bh3 !  ±  Threatening Nxf7 followed by Bxe6. } 16. Qc2 a5 17. Rfe1 Bf8 18. Bxf8 Rxf8 19. Nd6 { White's advantage is obvious; we just need to compare knights and bishops. White can trade his bishop for Black's knight anytime, while Black cannot make much use of his locked-in light-squared bishop. } 19... Rb8 { 19...Ne7 ?  loses to  20.Nxb5 ! } 20. Be4 h6 { If   20...g6  then White is likely to proceed with  21.Qd2  Ne7  22.h4 !  followed by h4-h5-hxg6 with a powerful attack. } 21. Qd2 Bd7 { More stubborn is   21...Ne7  though White progresses without difficulty, for example  22.Qf4  Bd7  23.h4  Qc7  24.h5  Nc8  25.Rac1  Ne7  26.Qe5  (threatening Nxf7)  f6  27.Qf4  Nc8  28.Bd3 !?  ±  White threatens Qe4-h7 } 22. Bxd5 { Good timing; the battle between White's knight and Black's bishop is easily won. } 22... cxd5 { Or   22...exd5  23.Re5  Qf6  24.f4  b4  25.Rae1  when the invasion down the e-file decides the game. } 23. Rac1 Qc7 24. g4 { Announcing a decisive kingside attack.    Preventing g4-g5. } 24... f6 { Instead   24...b4  25.g5  h5  or   25...hxg5  26.Qxg5  followed by Kh1, Rg1 winning.  26.Qf4  Bc6  27.Re3  g6  28.Rf3  Qe7  29.Qe5  then the win is imminent after Rf6 and one of many tactical shots, such as f2-f4-f5. } 25. f4 b4 26. f5 { Opening the e-file decisively. The rest is easy. } 26... exf5 27. gxf5 Be8 28. Re3 Rd8 29. Rce1 Bc6 30. Qg2 Rd7 { 30...Rxd6 ?  31.Re7 !  and wins. } 31. Qg6 Qa7 32. Re8 Rxd6 33. R8e7 { Final remarks  1. Throughout the entire game, White's d4-pawn was never vulnerable and the d5-square did not do much for Black, hence the c4-c5 move did not really weaken anything.   2. The move c4-c5 prevented essentially all of Black's attempts for counterplay. In particular, Black's light-squared bishop proved useless throughout the game.   3. 11...Be7 was a serious mistake, as it allowed White to seize control of the crucial d6-square, which was essential in White's victory.   4. Finally, this game serves as another example of White's positional advantage if the breaks ...c6-c5 and ...e6-e5 are impossible. Black's imprecise opening condemned him to this type of inferiority from the very beginning. } *

