{ @@HeaderStart@@Conrad Holt - Gata Kamsky, Saint Louis 2013@@HeaderEnd@@  Learning objective:  This game is an example of Black's successful ...c6-c5 break followed by an attack against White's king. } 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 a6 5. e3 g6 6. h3 Bg7 7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O e6 9. b3 Re8 10. Bb2 Nbd7 11. Qc2 b6 12. Rfd1 Bb7 13. e4 dxe4 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. Bxe4 { The key position has been reached; Black manages to free his position with the nice sequence: } 15... f5 16. Bd3 c5 { Black has solved his space problem and now White must play carefully to maintain equality. } 17. Be2 { The tempting  17.d5 ?!  Bxb2  runs into:  18.Qxb2  Qf6 !   But not  18...exd5 ?!  19.cxd5  Bxd5  20.Bxa6  with a complicated game  19.Qxf6  Nxf6  The d5-pawn is now pinned!  20.dxe6  Bxf3  21.gxf3  Rxe6  ∓ } 17... Qe7 18. dxc5 bxc5 { The alternative  18...Nxc5  19.Bxg7  Qxg7  is okay too, but it gives more mobility to White's queenside majority. } 19. Bxg7 Qxg7 { We have reached a critical moment in the game. Black's plan in quite clear: he must advance his pawn majority on the kingside and possibly create some threats against the king. White must create counterplay by pushing his majority on the queenside, but this is not easy as after b3-b4 the c4-pawn will be vulnerable. Black's position is not necessarily superior from an objective perspective, but the reader should understand that conducting Black's side will be a much simpler task than White's. } 20. Qd2 Re7 21. b4 { There are no other constructive plans. } 21... e5 22. bxc5 Nxc5 23. Qa5 Rc8 24. Rab1 { More accurate is  24.Rd8+  Rxd8  25.Qxd8+  Qf8  26.Qa5   Trading queens with  26.Qxf8+ ?!  Kxf8  leads to an unpleasant endgame due to Black's superior pawn structure, for example  27.Rd1  Ke8  28.Nd2  Rd7  29.Nb3  Rxd1+  30.Bxd1  Nd3  =+ and only Black can play for a win  26...Re8  27.Nd2  Qe7  When chances are approximately level. } 24... Ree8 { More accurate is  24...e4 !  25.Nd4   The endgame arising after  25.Rd8+  Rxd8  26.Qxd8+  Qf8  27.Qxf8+  Kxf8  =+ is uncomfortable for White  25...e3 !?  with good attacking chances for Black. } 25. Nd2 e4 26. Nb3 Ne6 { Of course Black does not wish to trade pieces yet, as it is difficult for White to create threats effectively. } 27. c5 { It is easy to see that this weak and isolated pawn will not get very far.   Safer is  27.Qd2  Qe5  though Black has a comfortable game. } 27... e3 { Beginning to create threats against White's king. } 28. fxe3 Qe5 29. Qd2 Rcd8 { An option was  29...Red8 !?  30.Qe1  Qxe3+  31.Qf2  Qxf2+  32.Kxf2  with roughly level chances   But of course not  29...Nxc5 ??  30.Nxc5  Qxc5  31.Rxb7  and wins. } 30. Qe1 Bd5 { Black wants to keep the game sharp.   The alternative  30...Rxd1  31.Rxd1  Nxc5  simplifies too much for Black's ambitions. } 31. Bxa6 Ra8 32. Bb5 { White miscalculates in a difficult position.   Necessary was  32.Bf1  Rxa2  when Black enjoys good compensation for the pawn. } 32... Rxa2 33. Rxd5 { If  33.Nd2  Rea8  Black has a very dangerous initiative   While  33.Bxe8 ??  loses immediately after  Rxg2+  34.Kf1  Qh2  with forced checkmate. } 33... Qxd5 34. e4 { 34.Qf1  Re7  -+ doesn't help either. } 34... fxe4 35. Bxe8 e3 { This is probably what White missed when he decided to play 32.Bb5. } 36. Bf7+ { A humorous resource.   Black is winning after  36.Qg3  Nf4 !  since  37.Qxf4 ?  Qxg2#  is mate. } 36... Kxf7 37. Qg3 Kg7 { Preparing 38...Nf4.   But of course not  37...Nf4 ??  38.Qxf4+ } 38. Nc1 Nf4 { Final remarks  1. The reader should remember Black's 18...bxc5. This move played a key role as it made it difficult for White to advance his queenside majority. Meanwhile, Black had a healthy kingside attack based on advancing his central majority.   2. Although White was objectively no worse until move 33, he lacked targets and his position was quite difficult on a practical level. The key to everything was White's lack of a healthy pawn majority since the passed c5-pawn was more of a weakness than a threat. } *

